cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.RO, cs.NE 

This paper deals with learning models of intuitive physics directly from raw visual observations, which involves computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG). The authors use unsupervised learning principles (cs.AI) to track mechanically-salient objects in videos and to train visual motion predictors that can take the underlying environment into account. The paper also involves robotics (cs.RO) as the authors introduce a new dataset of real objects rolling on complex terrains. Finally, the authors use convolutional neural networks (cs.NE) as their choice of architecture.
